      "text": "The NYISO\nInterconnection \nProcess\nIndependent System Operator\nNew York ISO\nJanuary 2023\nMaintaining Reliability\nfor a Grid in Transition\nNe2 | THE w YoNYISO INTERCONNECTION PROCESS rk ISO\nIntroduction\nState and federal clean energy policies are driving an historic transition of the existing electric \ngenerating fleet in New York, including a dramatic increase in the development of clean energy projects. \nMandates under the state’s Climate Leadership and Community Protection Act (CLCPA) require 70% \nrenewable energy by 2030 and an emissions-free electric system by 2040. The Inflation Reduction Act, \nsigned into law by President Biden in August 2022, makes $370 billion available in tax credits and\nincentives to speed the country’s transition to clean energy technology – the most aggressive climate \nrelated action ever taken by Congress. \nThe increase in investment in large scale renewable generating facilities and new clean energy \ntechnology is also driving a transition of the transmis",
      "highlights": [
        " the state’s Climate Leadership and Community Protection Act (CLCPA) require 70%  ...    The process for bringing a renewable project from a concept to commercial operation is complex and multifaceted. The process of performing necessary interconnection studies is only one of many  ...    acceptance, and permitting. In addition to the interconnection process administered by the New York  ...    and their investors. The interconnection process is a key factor and milestone for generation  ...    We discuss below the mechanics and requirements of the interconnection process, as well as  ...    largely by the CLCPA. \nThe NYISO's current efforts to identify and implement  ...    THE NYISO INTERCONNECTION PROCESS | 3 New Yor\nMaintaining Reliability\nInterconnecting to the Grid The interconnection process ensures “open access” to the transmission grid for new supply resources seeking to enter operation and is an essential element in maintaining the performance and reliability characteristics of the electric system on behalf of customers. Studying the impacts of each new proposed facility is a major responsibility, requiring expertise and careful analysis to determine if upgrades are necessary to maintain the reliability and safety of the electric system. The process is coordinated by the NYISO but requires significant involvement by  ...    of the process depends on coordination and timely delivery of information by all participants. The NYISO focuses on balancing the demands of open access to the electric system with preserving grid reliability and doing so at the most efficient cost to consumers. The NYISO processes have been  ...    process strives to strike a balance between the timely execution of the studies, and the flexibility that developers desire as they optimize project design. Within the NYISO Interconnection Process, all proposed new generation and transmission projects must enter an “interconnection queue,” where the proposals undergo a series of studies and detailed analysis that serve two key functions on behalf of customers: • Determinations of whether adding a new resource creates reliability issues on the system; and • If the project does impact system reliability, determine what system upgrades are necessary to interconnect the project while maintaining system reliability, and the costs of those upgrades. Under the process, the costs of equipment and upgrades required to connect projects are assigned to project developers, and in some cases, the local utility, not consumers. The interconnection process is required to identify the lowest cost solution to solve the reliability need. The allocation of upgrade costs identified through the process are not subject to negotiation, providing an important element of  ...    Ne4 | THE w YoNYISO INTERCONNECTION PROCESS rk ISO There are three types of interconnection requests that the NYISO analyzes. These include: • Generator additions intended to increase the amount of supply available to the grid;  ...    The NYISO interconnection process for generators generally involves up to three successive \nengineering studies: Optional Feasibility Study – evaluation of the configuration and local system impacts to inform  ...    System Impact Study – a single project study to evaluate the impact of the proposed project  ...    Facilities Study – evaluates the cumulative impact of a group of projects that have completed  ...    their proposal. Developers choosing to remain in the queue based on the results of feasibility and/or  ...    impact the group of projects have on the grid. The NYISO then assesses the cost to each developer  ...    THE NYISO INTERCONNECTION PROCESS | 5 New Yor If at the conclusion of the process one or more developers decline to accept these costs, the NYISO must remove the projects and perform another round of reliability studies. The NYISO will also reassess  ...    The NYISO has historically enjoyed a positive track record of reliably integrating"
